class Solution:
    def minTimeToVisitAllPoints(self, points: List[List[int]]) -> int:
        time = 0
        
        for i in range(1, len(points)):
            x1, y1 = points[i-1]
            x2, y2 = points[i]
            
            dx = abs(x2 - x1)
            dy = abs(y2 - y1)
            
            # Chebyshev distance = max(dx, dy)
            # Because diagonal move covers 1 step in both directions in 1 second
            time += max(dx, dy)
        
        return time

"""
Approach & Reasoning:

To move from point A (x1,y1) to point B (x2,y2):
- You can move horizontally, vertically, or diagonally.
- Each move costs 1 second.
- Diagonal move reduces both |dx| and |dy| by 1 in one second.

Therefore, the minimum time is the Chebyshev distance: max(|x2-x1|, |y2-y1|).

- First, you can use diagonal moves min(dx, dy) times â†’ reduces both differences.
- Then, you need |dx-dy| straight moves in the remaining direction.

So total seconds = max(dx, dy).

We just sum this value between every consecutive pair of points.

Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(1)
"""
